Action.author: jfbender
Action.body:
As far as I can tell there are no set collection of documents that are explicitly required, however, there are categories or classes of files and documents. It seems these mostly match the core practice areas. The goal is to demonstrate that you are actively executing or tracking these areas.
ALL supporting documents are due in the MSE server BEFORE access closes before EOSP. Specific access closure date/time is TBD, but usually 24-48 hours before EOSP.
0) Presentation: Slides and any handout material 1) Planning and Tracking: Strategic and tactical planning and tracking. How are we doing it and why? Is it working? Why? 2) Context and Requirements Management: How are we gathering requirements and analyzing requirements? Was it effective? How do we know? What are our key requirements to talk about? 3) Quality Management: How are we identifying software quality areas and what are we doing about them? What are our key quality attributes and why? How are we tracking them through the project? How will we measure them? How will we ensure that they are met? 4) Configuration Management: What are we doing for configuration management? What are we tracking with it? Why? Is it working? 5) Architectural Design: What is our architectural process? Why? How did we implement the process? What are our key architectural views or elements? How did we map architectural drivers (functional, non-functional, and constraints)? How is it working? 6) Risk management: What is our risk tracking process? What are our key risks? How did we mitigate or handle them? Anything key still on-going? Is our process working?
7) Orthogonal issues: These are things that don't fit into other categories. Personnel issues, technologies, or things that went well or didn't. Any other problems we had? So discussing the addition of Daniel to the project and how we handled that and why.
8) Future: Talking about how we are going to finish architecture and begin constructing. Also, we might want to have an idea of what our construction process and procedures we think we might be following and why. Even if we haven't decided on something.

Action.author: ashutosh dube
Action.body: Thanks Jonathan. This is a really nice description of what we should think while creating and grouping our documents. For I am now creating a list of documents we have with their status that I can see from the document. We can discuss how we can incorporate above ideas in our documents in our tomorrows meeting.

Status.name: Open

Status.name: Reopened
Status.description: This issue was once resolved, but the resolution was deemed incorrect. From here issues are either marked assigned or resolved.

Status.name: Resolved
Status.description: A resolution has been taken, and it is awaiting verification by reporter. From here issues are either reopened, or are closed.

Status.name: Closed
Status.description: The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are closed can be reopened.

Status.name: Building
Status.description: Source code has been committed, and JIRA is waiting for the code to be built before moving to the next status.

Status.name: Build Broken
Status.description: The source code committed for this issue has possibly broken the build.
